  "prompt": "What is a boy/girl called when he/she is 1-6 years old, 6-11years old, 11-14 years old, and 14-18 years old?",
  "response": "Children and adolescents are typically categorized into several age groups, each with specific terms that describe their developmental stages. Below are the commonly used terms for each of the age ranges you specified:\n\n### 1-6 Years Old\n- **Term:** **Early Childhood** or **Preschooler**\n- **Description:** This stage includes toddlers and young children who are developing fundamental motor skills, language, and basic social interactions. They are often attending preschool or kindergarten.\n\n### 6-11 Years Old\n- **Term:** **School-age Child** or **Middle Childhood**\n- **Description:** Children in this age range are usually enrolled in elementary school. They experience significant cognitive development, improve social skills, and gain greater independence.\n\n### 11-14 Years Old\n- **Term:** **Preteen** or **Tween**\n- **Description:** This transitional period bridges childhood and adolescence. Preteens begin to develop more complex thinking abilities and may start to seek greater autonomy from their parents. They are on the cusp of puberty and the associated physical and emotional changes.\n\n### 14-18 Years Old\n- **Term:** **Teenager** or **Adolescent**\n- **Description:** Teenagers undergo significant physical, emotional, and psychological changes as they move towards adulthood. This stage includes high school years, increased responsibility, identity exploration, and preparation for adult roles.\n\n**Note:** These terms are generally **gender-neutral**, meaning they apply equally to boys and girls. However, in some contexts, people might specify \"boy\" or \"girl\" (e.g., \"teenage boy\" or \"adolescent girl\") to highlight gender-specific experiences or issues.\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Age Range | Term                |\n|-----------|---------------------|\n| 1-6       | Early Childhood / Preschooler |\n| 6-11      | School-age Child / Middle Childhood |\n| 11-14     | Preteen / Tween     |\n| 14-18     | Teenager / Adolescent |\n\nThese classifications help educators, parents, and professionals tailor their approaches to the developmental needs of children and adolescents at each stage.",
